                            <comment id="15115332" author="apachespark" created="Mon, 25 Jan 2016 14:59:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;User &apos;poolis&apos; has created a pull request for this issue:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/spark/pull/10899&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/spark/pull/10899&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15260031" author="eniemela" created="Wed, 27 Apr 2016 12:17:45 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;With pyspark this Oracle FLOAT-error appears with exception &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;ValueError: (ValueError(u&apos;Could not parse datatype: decimal(38,-127)&apos;,)
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Workaround: in Oracle query, cast FLOAT to NUMBER if precision and scale can be set so that all data can be included. If not, convert FLOATs with TO_CHAR and change type later, eg.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;sql = &quot;(SELECT TO_CHAR(float_column) AS FLOAT_COLUMN FROM some_table)&quot;
df = sc.read.format(&apos;jdbc&apos;).options(.. table=sql)

df = df.withColumn(&quot;FLOAT_COLUMN&quot;, df[&quot;FLOAT_COLUMN&quot;].cast(&quot;float&quot;))
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
